                            <h2>
                                Has COVID-19 Pandemic Made Business Card Redundant? Time to Switch Over to Virtual Business Cards
                            </h2>
                            <div class="col-lg-12 d-flex align-items-center" data-aos="zoom-out" data-aos-delay="200">

                                <img src="~/homeassets/img/blog_banner.png" class="img-fluid" alt="virtual business card">

                            </div>
                            <p>
                                From CEOs to fresh college graduates and even freelancers, business cards have played a crucial role in promoting a business and networking with new people. It is a cost-effective way for businesses and freelancers to advertise about their business or brand. Yes, it is a fact that most people would take your card and keep it somewhere only to find it after some years. However, seeing the physical card will prompt an individual to contact you if he/she is in need of any of your products or services.
                            </p>

                            <div class="row gx-0">
                                <div class="col-lg-7 d-flex flex-column justify-content-center" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="200">
                                    <div class="contentsss">
                                        <p>
                                            Traditional business cards have been in existence for many centuries. However, the COVID-19 pandemic has led to a drastic decline in the use of business cards and made them completely redundant. In the COVID-19 world, there have been less face-to-face interactions between people, meetings switched over to the digital mode, cancellation of several events, work from home, social distancing, and going contactless in everything. Most organizations across the globe are working from home. The question that arises in the mind of everyone is – Are business cards dead? The answer to this question is Yes. With no face-to-face networking events happening, business cards have lost their significance. Zoom calls, Google Meet, and video conferencing have become the new normal to meet and connect with new people. The digital world and virtual meetings have opened the door for something new – digital or virtual business cards.
                                        </p>
                                        <h3>Reasons why business cards are dead – at least at present in the pandemic world</h3>
                                        <p>
                                            <b>The rise of smartphones</b>
                                        </p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                In today’s digital world, smartphones have become a one-stop solution for everything.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>The smartphone follows people wherever they go.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Whether you want to connect with a client on Instagram or add them on your official LinkedIn page, everything is possible through a smartphone.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Social media apps like LinkedIn, Facebook, Twitter, and chat applications like WhatsApp and Telegram have changed everything.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                With so many options, a physical business card looks like a thing of the past.
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                </div>

                                <div class="col-lg-5 d-flex align-items-center" data-aos="zoom-out" data-aos-delay="200">
                                    <div class="content" style="padding:21px;width:100%;">
                                        <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/RBPB7Etc4_g?autoplay=1&amp;rel=0"
                                                allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"
                                                mozallowfullscreen="mozallowfullscreen"
